Manager.Unnamed: 4: C-level executives form the backbone of a company's leadership, steering the organization toward sustainable growth and success. Their comprehensive business knowledge, leadership skills, and ability to adapt to changing landscapes make them instrumental in shaping the company's present and future. Impact is long term in nature.
Manager.Unnamed: 5: Typically leads activites of the most significant business or functional areas through subordinate VPs and Directors
Manager.Unnamed: 6: Develops and provides strategy, vision and direction with company wide impact and implications. Develops company wide policies and practices. Provides input to CEO, BOD and shareholders. Accountable for company-wide financial outcomes which impact organization performance
Manager.Unnamed: 7: Responsible for making strategic decisions, shaping the company's direction, and overseeing various aspects of its operations.
Manager.Unnamed: 8: Reports to the CEO and is a member of the company’s Senior Leadership Team (SLT). Interfaces with the Board of Directors and represents the company to outside stakeholders
Manager.Unnamed: 9: Embodies the company culture. Nurtures and evolves the artifacts of the company culture.  Leadership style aligned with cultural norms of the company. Lead by example, strategic thinking, effective communications, resolute decison making, accountability, collaboration, empowerment, adaptability, innovation, resilience, ethical conduct, employee development, customer focus. Models and enables inclusive culture.
Manager.Unnamed: 10: Leads the strategic direction of their organizational responsiblity; Arbiter for the allocation of resources with their organization; Models and enforces the cultural and peformance norms of the organization; Ultimate responsible party for organizational success of failure. Board of Director approval required for entry to this level.
Manager.Unnamed: 11: Determines the when and how to act to support initiatives. Determines resource allocations and ensures both stakeholder management and cross functional collaboration occurs in support of strategic and tactical initatives

Manager.Unnamed: 4: Fully responsible for a major sub function of a larger functional organization. Establishes strategic plans for owned functions based on corporate strategy and financial goals. Strategic decisions are critical to functional and company performance and likely have shorter term impact (> 2 years). Manages change and risk. Responsibilities are generally global.
Manager.Unnamed: 5: Typically leads activities of one more related functional groups. with director level direct reports. May have VP level direct reports for VPs who are also classified as a "Top Job" and member of SLT
Manager.Unnamed: 6: Develops and provides strategy, vision and direction with departmental implications. Develops department policies and practices and contributes to company wide policies and practices. Provides input to C Level leadership and as needed to the CEO and board. Accountable for department-wide financial outcomes, strategic and tactical outcomes which impact organization performance
Manager.Unnamed: 7: Responsible for making strategic decisions, shaping the departmental or functional direction, and overseeing various aspects of its operations.
Manager.Unnamed: 8: Typically reports to a C Level executive or other SLT leader. May be a member of the Company's Senior Leadership Team if a Top functional or business line executive
Manager.Unnamed: 9: Embodies the company culture. Nurtures and evolves the artifacts of the company culture.  Leadership style is wholly aligned with cultural norms of the company. Lead by example, strategic thinking, effective communications, resolute decison making, accountability, collaboration, empowerment, adaptability, innovation, resilience, ethical conduct, employee development, customer focus
Manager.Unnamed: 10: Leads the operational approaches and programs that supports organizational strategy and goals; Determines resource needs and influences resource investments at the corporate level; Develops functional orgs to meet company objectives; Models culture and performance norms and enforces alignment
Manager.Unnamed: 11: Translates strategic business objectives into operational outcomes.

Manager.Unnamed: 4: Establishes and develops broad company strategy and translates into multi functional objectives. Erroneous decisions will affect the company’s mid to long term success.
Manager.Unnamed: 5: Typically leads activities of one or more functional areas through subordinate directors/managers especially in larger units of the organization, who have overall responsibility for the success of their assigned areas. Oversees teams to develop new methods to solve company wide matters
Manager.Unnamed: 6: Develops and provides strategy, vision and direction to multiple functions. Implements company wide policies and practices. Provides input to executive management. Accountable for function financial outcomes which impact organization performance
Manager.Unnamed: 7: Consistently works with abstract ideas and circumstances, across functional areas of the business. Through assessment of intangible variables, identifies and evaluates fundamental issues, providing strategy and direction to functional areas. Anticipates factors that could influence strategies and company results.
Manager.Unnamed: 8: Interacts with internal and external executive level management, requiring negotiation of critical matters. Influences policy making, communication strategies. High levels of persuasion skills are necessary. Recognized as an influential leader.
Manager.Unnamed: 9: Models the company culture. Contributes to the development of company culture. Ensures company culture norms are present and managed at the departmental/team level. Lead by example, strategic thinking, effective communications, resolute decison making, accountability, collaboration, empowerment, adaptability, innovation, resilience, ethical conduct, employee development, customer focus
Manager.Unnamed: 10: Functional and managerial expertise evident. Translates strategic intentions into operational planning and oversight. Allocates resources to meet organizational objectives
Manager.Unnamed: 11: Inspires action, coordinates simultaneous initiatives of high importance to the company

Manager.Unnamed: 4: Contributes to the development of functional strategies. Erroneous decisions will have near and mid term impact on organizational success.
Manager.Unnamed: 5: Directs the activities of a functional area through lower management levels. Leads teams to develop new methods and solve complex matters. Direct reports typically Senior Manager, Manager, and high level individual contributors
Manager.Unnamed: 6: Participates with senior management to establish strategic plans and objectives. Makes final decisions on implementation and ensures operational effectiveness. Cascades functional strategy and contributes to organizational policies. Accountable for actions that impact their function’s overall budgetary outcomes.
Manager.Unnamed: 7: Works on complex issues where problems are not clearly defined and where the fundamental principles do not fully apply. Translates business strategy into functional plans and guides execution. Participates in the development of methods, techniques and evaluation criteria for projects and people. Ensure budget and schedules meet expecations.
Manager.Unnamed: 8: Interacts with senior management, executives, major external customers and partners, which frequently involves negotiating matters of significance to the function. Reconciles multiple shareholder views to drive results.
Manager.Unnamed: 9: Models the company culture. Contributes to the development of company culture. Ensures company culture norms are present and managed at the departmental/team level. Strong exemplar of company values.  Behaviors are consistently aligned with company expectations.
Manager.Unnamed: 10: Effectively aligns team/ dept resources to meet objectives.  Ensures team members are fully aligned and accountable to team goals and outcomes.  Close gaps in capability and resources to attain desired results
Manager.Unnamed: 11: Strategic battle-tested leader, directs operational units to meet and exceed organizational objectives

Manager.Unnamed: 4: Erroneous decisions will result in critical delay(s) in schedules and/or unit operations and may jeopardize overall business activities. Decisions directly impact short-term, less than one-year results of the team/ program/group.
Manager.Unnamed: 5: Manages activities of two or more disciplines or a department. Oversees experienced level professionals and/or may be responsible for subordinate managers. Frequently advises team(s) on moderately complex matters.
Manager.Unnamed: 6: Establish operational objectives, policies, procedures and work plans and delegates assignments to team members. Develops, modifies and executes organizational policies that affect immediate operations and may also have company-wide effect. Accountable for department budget.
Manager.Unnamed: 7: Works on issues where analysis requires conceptual thinking and in-depth knowledge of organizational objectives. Problems may not be clearly defined and may lack strategic connection. Implements policies. Selects methods, techniques and evaluation criteria to achieve desired results. Drives the strategy and success of larger projects which contribute to their functional area and may contribute to multiple areas of the organization.
Manager.Unnamed: 8: Interacts regularly with lower and/or senior management on matters concerning assigned functional areas, departments, and/or customers. Requires the ability to persuade others in sensitive and complex situations, while preserving relationships. Applies knowledge to convince other stakeholders on desired departmental outcomes.
Manager.Unnamed: 9: Leads teams to embody cultural norms. Consistently models company values
Manager.Unnamed: 10: Effectively aligns team/ dept resources to meet objectives.  Ensures team members are fully aligned and accountable to team goals and outcomes.  Close gaps in capability and resources to attain desired results
Manager.Unnamed: 11: Strong tactical decision maker, handles unforeseen issues and overcomes moderate obstacles independently

Manager.Unnamed: 4: Translates functional plans into operational processes and guides execution. Erroneous decisions or failure to achieve results will add to costs and may have an impact that lasts up to a year.
Manager.Unnamed: 5: Manages the activities of multiple sections or a discipline through subordinate supervisors and/or professionals. Guides by function or department practices and well defined management precedents.
Manager.Unnamed: 6: Receives objective oriented assignments and determines resources to meet schedules and goals. Provides guidance to team members within the latitude of company / organizational policy. Recommends changes to policies and establishes procedures to meet objectives.
Manager.Unnamed: 7: Works on issues of diverse scope where analysis and evaluation of various factors is required. Follows processes and operational norms in selecting methods and techniques to develop solutions. Develops and manages operational initiatives to deliver tactical results.
Manager.Unnamed: 8: Interacts frequently with subordinate supervisors, customers, and/or functional peer group professionals, involving matters between sections and multiple units. Partners with key contacts outside their own area of expertise and other external stakeholders. Effectively communicates and presents results and recommendations across disciplines.
Manager.Unnamed: 10: Effectively aligns team resources to meet objectives.  Ensures team members are fully aligned and accountable to team goals and outcomes.  Influences leadership to close gaps to produce dept/org outcomes
Manager.Unnamed: 11: Experienced management capability. Front line manager - first true full fledged managerial level

Manager.Unnamed: 4: Develops and manages routine operational plans. Erroneous decisions or failure to achieve results will cause delays in schedules. Meets targets typically against a monthly plan.
Manager.Unnamed: 5: Provides direct supervision to professional individual contributors and/or skilled and support individual contributors. Acts as guide to unit or sub-units and may become actively involved, as required, to meet schedules and resolve problems.
Manager.Unnamed: 6: Receives assignments based on incremental objectives and defined processes. Provides direction to employees according to established policies and management guidance. Administers company policies that directly affect subordinate employees. Recommends changes to group relevant policies. Takes actions to monitor and manage costs as needed.
Manager.Unnamed: 7: Works on issues requiring the analysis of data, relevant factors and resolves problems. Exercises judgment and interpretation to help define procedures and policies to determine appropriate action.
Manager.Unnamed: 8: Interacts with subordinate supervisors and functional peer groups. Interaction requires interpreting and explaining information to audiences familiar with the subject. Gains cooperation of others, conducting presentations of technical information concerning specific projects or programs.
Manager.Unnamed: 10: Effectively manages the transactional output of assigned team members.  Models basis managerial capability and is comfortable escalating to higher levels team or indivdual issues
Manager.Unnamed: 11: Skills/training needed. Manages transactional teams to meet company objectives

Professional.Unnamed: 4: Capable of working on small projects with close direction
Professional.Unnamed: 5: Learn to use professional concepts. Applies knowledge and basic problem solving techniques to define and resolve problems. Determines a course of action based on guidelines.
Professional.Unnamed: 6: Works on problems of limited scope. Follows standard practices and procedures in analyzing situations or data from which answers can be readily obtained. Work is reviewed periodically based on a set of defined procedures or precedence. Normally receives general instruction on work and new assignments.
Professional.Unnamed: 7: Develops stable working relationships internally. Exchanges standard/basic information with colleagues and immediate supervisor, project leaders and other professionals in the team/group.
Professional.Unnamed: 8: Typically requires no previous professional experience.
Professional.Unnamed: 9: A good cultural fit for Thumbtack. Generally models company values
Professional.Unnamed: 10: Entry level of professional careers - learning the role; Core skills/expertise is limiated; Requires detailed direction; Focused on learning, growth and contributing as a teammate

Professional.Unnamed: 3: Principal | World class (Sr. Director level equivalent)
Professional.Unnamed: 4: Sought by senior management (C Level, VP) for advice. Provides vision and road map to navigate major transformational trends within their functional/industry orbit. Represents the company externally with singular domain authority. For many job families we do not have a need for L8 individual contributors
Professional.Unnamed: 5: Serves as an expert in the field and principal advisor. Provides, guides and uses professional concepts in developing resolution to critical issues. Applies extensive knowledge of theories, practices and design matters. Leads the application of existing principles and guides development of new ideas.
Professional.Unnamed: 6: Works on issues that impact program success or addresses future concepts and products. Solutions are devised based on limited information and require judgment. Implementation of solutions requires a longer term view which impacts strategic goals and objectives. Results impact multiple functions.
Professional.Unnamed: 7: Exercises wide latitude in determining objectives and approaches to critical assignments. Creates formal networks with key decision makers and is widely recognized as expert and thought leader by both internal and external communities. Serves as external spokesperson for the organization regarding specialty topics
Professional.Unnamed: 8: Typically requires a minimum of 15 years of related experience with a Bachelor’s degree; or 12 years and a Master’s degree; or a PhD with 8 years experience; or equivalent experience. Significant barriers to entry (e.g., top management review, approval) exist at this level
Professional.Unnamed: 9: Be a standard bear of Thumbtack culture. Manifest and propagate the culture in every interaction. Consistently models company values. Serves as a examplar of culture and behaviors while creating signfiicant value to the company
Professional.Unnamed: 10: Visionary - Major influence on company and industry; Rare - generally only exists in technical development organizations; industry luminary; Significant barriers to entry

Professional.Unnamed: 4: Provides innovative breakthroughs to the toughest challenges. Influences management on strategic direction. Will have an impact on multiple organizations, regions, and/or disciplines as well as external parties/partners. Not all job families include level L7. Owns and is accountable for large projects and initiatives. May be responsible for Xfn deliverables. Can step aside from the lead role to allow others to learn and grow. Focuses on highest priority projects
Professional.Unnamed: 5: Applies broad expertise and knowledge in highly specialized fields or several related disciplines. Leads and contributes to development of company objectives and principles to achieve goals in creative and effective ways.
Professional.Unnamed: 6: Works on significant and unique issues where analysis of situations or data requires an evaluation of intangibles. Uses conceptual thinking to understand advanced issues and implications. Exercises independent judgment in methods, techniques and evaluation criteria for obtaining results. Accountable for results, which may impact the entire function.
Professional.Unnamed: 7: Creates formal networks involving coordination among groups. Focuses on providing thought leadership and works on broader organization projects, which requires understanding of wider business concepts. Requires conveying advanced information and persuading several diverse stakeholders/audiences. Recognized internally as a subject matter expert. May direct the activities of others.
Professional.Unnamed: 8: Typically requires a minimum of 12 years of related experience with a Bachelor’s degree; or 8 years and a Master’s degree; or a PhD with 5 years experience; or equivalent experience. Barriers to entry may require committee review. Demonstrated capability may transcend experience expectations
Professional.Unnamed: 9: Be a standard bearer of Thumbtack culture. Manifest and propagate the culture in every interaction. High alignment with company values is implicit at this level.  Strong mentorship behaviors required.
Professional.Unnamed: 10: Deep expertise/ unique knowledge, Broad impact, broad context; Provides breakthroughs and requires no direction; Partners regularly with the exec team; Provides mentorship and expertise to lower level team members;
Professional.Unnamed: 11: Knows more about rope than you ever will

Professional.Unnamed: 4: Brings domain expertise to complex projects. Level requires contribution outside the direct area of responsibility. Leadership role for cross functional projects. Owns or co-owns medium to large projects, executing with minimal guidance.
Professional.Unnamed: 5: Exhibits advanced wide-ranging experience, using in depth professional knowledge, acumen, concepts and company objectives to develop, resolve complex models and procedures. Provides solutions to issues in creative and effective ways. Understands the interrelationships of different disciplines. Directs the application of existing principles and guides development of new policies and ideas.
Professional.Unnamed: 6: Understands and works on complex issues where analysis of situations or data requires an in-depth evaluation of variable factors. Determines methods and procedures on new assignments. Exercises judgment in selecting methods, evaluating, adapting of complex techniques and evaluation criteria for obtaining results. Work is reviewed upon completion and is consistent with departmental objectives.
Professional.Unnamed: 7: Networks with key contacts outside their own area of expertise. Adapts style and uses persuasion in delivering messages that relate to the wider firm business. Frequently advises others on complex matters. May be accountable through the team for delivery of tactical business targets.
Professional.Unnamed: 8: Typically requires a minimum of 8 years of related experience with a Bachelor’s degree; or 6 years and a Master’s degree; or a PhD with 3 years experience; or equivalent experience. Some barriers to entry exist at this level, requiring department review. Demonstrated capability may transcend experience expectations
Professional.Unnamed: 9: Have positive interactions with Thumbtack team members. Team members find working with you to be additive and effective
Professional.Unnamed: 10: Go to functional expert; Provides project level leadership; Contributes outside direct area of expertise/responsibliity

Professional.Unnamed: 4: Represents an area of specialization within the organization. Independently resolves complex problems. Contributes to cross functional projects. Trains/mentors more junior colleagues. Works autonomously on medium to large complexity projects
Professional.Unnamed: 5: Complete knowledge and full understanding of areas of specialization, principles and practices within a professional discipline. Assesses unusual circumstances and uses sophisticated analytical and problem solving techniques to identify causes. Resolves and assesses a wide range of issues in creative ways and suggests variations in approach. This level is a fully qualified, experienced professional level.
Professional.Unnamed: 6: Works on problems of diverse scope where analysis of information requires evaluation of identifiable factors. Devises solutions based on limited information and precedent and adapts existing approaches to resolve issues. Uses evaluation, judgment, and interpretation to select the right course of action. Work is done independently and is reviewed at critical points.
Professional.Unnamed: 7: Enhances relationships and networks with senior internal/external partners who are not familiar with the subject matter often requiring persuasion. Adapts style to different audiences and often advises others on difficult matters.
Professional.Unnamed: 8: Typically requires a minimum of 5 years of related experience with a Bachelor’s degree; or 3 years and a Master’s degree; Demonstrated capability may transcend experience expectations
Professional.Unnamed: 9: Models the company culture and consistently displays company values
Professional.Unnamed: 10: Autonomous problem solver; Strong core sklls and expertise; requires infrequent direciton
Professional.Unnamed: 11: Calculates rope strength. Knows a lot about knots.

Professional.Unnamed: 4: Completes assignments/tasks which have clear, near-term objectives. Operates independently to perform routine tasks. Capable of working on medium size/complexity projects
Professional.Unnamed: 5: Develops professional expertise, applies company policies and procedures to resolve a variety of issues. Determines a course of action based on guidelines and modifies processes and methods as required.
Professional.Unnamed: 6: Works on problems of moderate scope, which are often varied and routine where analysis of situations or data requires a review of a variety of factors. Exercises judgment within defined procedures and practices to determine appropriate action. Applies learned techniques and contributes to analysis and investigation to solve problems. Normally receives little instruction on day-to-day work, general instructions on new assignments.
Professional.Unnamed: 7: Builds productive internal/external working relationships to resolve mutual problems by collaborating on procedures or transactions. Focuses on providing standard professional advice and creating initial reports/ analyzes for review by experienced team professionals.
Professional.Unnamed: 8: Typically requires a Bachelor’s degree and a minimum of 2 years of related experience; or an advanced degree without experience; or equivalent work experience. Demonstrated capability may transcend experience expectations
Professional.Unnamed: 9: A good cultural fit for Thumbtack. Generally models company values
Professional.Unnamed: 10: Task oriented but gaining/demonstrating independence; Core skills/expertise is functional; Requires some direciton
Professional.Unnamed: 11: Can tie basic knots. Shown complex knots.

Support.Knowledge & Application: As a highly skilled specialist, contributes to the development of concepts and techniques. Completes complex tasks in creative and effective ways.
Support.Complexity & Problem Solving: Consistently works on complex assignments requiring independent action and a high degree of initiative to resolve issues. Makes recommendations for new procedures.
Support.Collaboration & Interaction: Acts independently to determine methods and procedures on new assignments. Often acts as a facilitator and team leader.
Support.Typical Degree & Years of Experience: Typically requires a minimum of 6+ years of related experience.

Support.Knowledge & Application: As a skilled specialist, completes tasks in resourceful and effective ways.
Support.Complexity & Problem Solving: Works on assignments requiring considerable judgment and initiative. Understands implications of work and makes recommendations for solutions.
Support.Collaboration & Interaction: Determines methods and procedures on new assignments. May be informal team leader.
Support.Typical Degree & Years of Experience: Typically requires a minimum of 4 - 6 years of related experience.

Support.Knowledge & Application: Has substantial understanding of the job and applies knowledge and skills to complete a wide range of tasks.
Support.Complexity & Problem Solving: Works on assignments that are moderately difficult, requiring judgment in resolving issues or in making recommendations.
Support.Collaboration & Interaction: Normally receives little instruction on daily work, general instructions on newly introduced assignments.
Support.Typical Degree & Years of Experience: Typically requires a minimum of 2 - 4 years of related experience.

Support.Knowledge & Application: Applies acquired job skills and company policies and procedures to complete assigned tasks.
Support.Complexity & Problem Solving: Works on assignments that are semi-routine in nature but recognizes the need for occasional deviation from accepted practice.
Support.Collaboration & Interaction: Normally follows established procedures on routine work, requires instructions only on new assignments.
Support.Typical Degree & Years of Experience: Typically requires a minimum of 1 - 2 years of related experience.

Support.Knowledge & Application: Acquires job skills and learns company policies and procedures to complete routine tasks.
Support.Complexity & Problem Solving: Works on assignments that are routine in nature, requiring limited judgment. Has little or no role in decision-making.
Support.Collaboration & Interaction: Normally receives detailed instructions on all work. Works under close supervision.
Support.Typical Degree & Years of Experience: Typically requires less than 1 year of related experience.
